Higgs boson examined
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson caused a justified stir last summer.
There is an opinion that this boson is involved in the mechanism that is responsible for all matter in the universe.
And then there is the last particle whose existence is predicted by a standard model - our best or "least bad" explanation of the nature and behavior of matter - which has not yet been empirically observed.
However, there is still no 100% certainty among physicists that it is the Higgs boson.
There is no doubt that we have a completely new particle at our disposal that is very similar to the Higgs boson, as predicted by the standard model.
The new data released this week during the great physical congress in Kyoto confirms it rather, but all the data is still missing so that we can have absolute certainty.
However, let's assume it's the Higgs boson, as the risk of error seems small, and let's look at what's actually going on.
There is an unquestionable law in this world that says two things cannot happen at the same time in the same place.
This rule can not be circumvented - and do not try too hard, otherwise you will hurt yourself.
Although particle physics is a very strange world, it turns out that a similar law applies to it: Pauli's exclusion principle, according to which two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state" - this "state" roughly creates some of their properties.
Furthermore, it divides physical particles into two categories.
On the one hand, we find well-ordered citizens, or fermions, who obey Pauli’s principle.
And on the other end, the bosons move, submissive anarchists who do not appreciate anything at all - definitely not this principle, which means that they can easily be in the same place at the same time.
These bosons are further divided into two groups according to the device (by the way, absolutely amazing), which is The Particle Adventure, in the Berkeley laboratories: mesons, which we leave unnoticed here, and "force particles", by which the great natural forces are spread and with which the Higgs boson is the most famous.
However, it must be said that these bosons are not as exotic animals as one might think.
If you read this article, it is thanks to a boson with unusual banality: a photon, or "particle of light", which is the "carrier" of electromagnetic force.
When a particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes its direction, it "disrupts" the electromagnetic field in this particular place, much like a pebble thrown into a pond.
From this "disruption" an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.) arises and this wave is nothing but a photon - and therefore one of the bosons, "carriers of power".
A more stable field
The same goes for the Higgs boson, only with the difference that it takes another field, the Higgs field, to make this boson appear.
This Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; for its excitation it is necessary to achieve very high energy values, as with the frozen level of the pond, only a very large boulder is already gnawing.
For this reason, it is necessary to use such a huge accelerator part as the accelerator in the CERN laboratory - a large hadron accelerator with a 27 km circuit! - in order to develop such energy.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field once again lends itself to clarifying the relationship between Higgs and matter.
Not all particles and not all materials react with the electromagnetic field.
Some, for example, magnets do, but others do not - a piece of paper, for example, will never keep itself on the refrigerator.
And yet, not all particles react with the Higgs field: those that do have a certain mass, while others (such as a photon, let’s look at it) don’t.
And Mrs. Nov<0xC3><0xA1>kov<0xC3><0xA1> asks, what are all these researches that "bring us"?
From a scientific point of view, it is a confirmation of the validity of the standard model (SM), which allows physicists to examine any discrepancy between the observations and the predictions of the SM.
In addition, many physicists literally wish to be able to find them, because the slightest difference could open the space of "new physics" and heal some gaps in the model.
It should be noted that the model still has huge shortcomings, does not bring any clarification of gravity (ouch!) or dark matter, which makes up about 80% of the cosmic matter (again, ouch!).
However, CERN has so far not found such contradictions.
Responses
The responses of these researches in the daily life of Mr. and Mrs. Nov<0xC3><0xA1>kov<0xC3><0xA1> can only be very difficult to predict, but it would be a mistake to assume that there will be none.
Look, at the very beginning of the 1960s, the laser pioneers in Bell’s labs had no idea of the revolution that their work would bring about.
They assumed scientific use, but nothing else.
Physicist Willard Boyle - who worked at Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who created the first permanent laser beam (previous beams were pulsed) in 1962, I have already said - the laser was initially considered such a "toy to the laboratory".
Just imagine...
In addition, the application can also result from all the tools that surround the research.
For example, the same Willard Boyle created a small light sensor in 1969 during his work on optics.
This sensor, although initially unplanned by Boyle, now serves as the "eye" of all digital cameras in the world and won him the Nobel Prize in Physics in 2009.
Of course, this does not mean that the activities around the LHC necessarily have to change our lives, but it does mean that one never really knows...
