He looks back at the delicious breakfast and agrees that we will help him to eat.
He is brave and even smiles, talks to strangers who stop at him, brings him medicine, offers him a bath.
Dare to die in the ordinary.
"My greatest desire is to get rid of that diarrhea, it humiliates me," he confides.
A few hours later, a team of doctors found a cure for his problem.
"In life, you learn that men urinate in vests," says Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at the Victor-Gadbois facility.
Returning to the stage of a child is an unacceptable humiliation for some people.
"Depends on which person's abilities," says the psychologist.
According to the opinion of a number of persons engaged in palliative care, crucial moments take place at the very core of such a return.
Patients who enter the home with Victor-Gadbois palliative care all suffer from cancer.
Their prognosis is a maximum of three months of life.
At this stage, the team of doctors and nurses who take care of them does not provide them with so-called "medical" care.
In the case of Mrs. A., 89 years old, the worst fear is to die "of suffocation with full consciousness".
But the disease allowed me to discover my children.
"I have good children," he adds.
"I don't have any wishes in my life anymore," she says, and then she asks us to put her breathing apparatus on.
However, he is still looking forward to the last visit of his son from Italy in the next few days.
In the home of Victor-Gadbois, in cooperation with a group of volunteers, body care is provided with nutrition.
This is what palliative care looks like when nothing else can be done.
To make death more comfortable.
In Quebec, there is one palliative care bed per 11,700 inhabitants.
That is very little if we realize that we will all die one day.
Here life continues in optimal conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors in the house.
Whether it is a level of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
When a person dies, he can be given, for example, brandy or pepsi, according to taste.
Diabetics no longer need to monitor their sugar levels.
Death is a part of everyday life.
Last night, they were carrying a beer to Mr. X., who died later that night.
This morning, his son drinks a beer in honor of his late father.
"We are helping patients as well as their loved ones," says Nathalie Savard, director of nursing services.
In the house of Victor-Gadbois, days go by one after another, but they do not resemble each other.
In addition to a thirty-nine-year-old man who rejoices at the last meeting with his family, thoroughly grounded on pillows, while they drink in his honor, a thirty-six-year-old man tragically dies surrounded by his parents, a woman and two small children, after having the opportunity to try everything.
"For six months, there are always three to five beds, which are designed for people with cancer under 45 years old," says Dr. Christiane Martel.
53% of patients who come to the Victor-Gadbois home come from their homes, and 47% come from hospitals.
Problems with access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, i.e., care that is designed to alleviate suffering once the sick person reaches the final stage of his or her life, whether at home, in the hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the Victor-Gadbois home and the Grand Montréal Home Palliative Care Society, specialize more or less exclusively in the care provided to oncology patients.
And it is precisely this fundamental unavailability of health care in Quebec that leads many physicians specializing in palliative care to fear the adoption of the law on euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Since October, a manifesto has been in circulation signed by palliative care leaders such as Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, in which they demonstrate their disagreement with such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, the Quebec health care system is not powerful enough to ensure that everyone has access to quality palliative care before it is possible to agree to euthanasia.
She says she recently experienced a patient who spent 14 days on standby in enormous pain, without anyone taking the necessary steps to relieve her.
He is afraid that patients will not be asked to die because they do not receive proper care.
And at the same time, a number of oncologists take care of their patients until the last moments, regardless of the adverse prognosis.
Hél<0xC3><0xA8>ne Richard’s chances of survival were already very low when she left the demanding chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was ending my treatment, she said she regretted that I had stopped fighting, she told us.
And yet she told me it was over!
There is no omnipotent care.
Dr. Martel estimates that 90% of patients who wish to die thank their attending physicians for not fulfilling their wishes when their palliative care team alleviated their pain.
But it must be said that palliative care is definitely not omnipotent in the treatment of pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, director of palliative care at the Grand Montréal Home Palliative Care Society, patients are prevented from treating pain in 8% of cases.
At the very end of life, doctors often use a palliative sedative, which the patient falls asleep until the moment of death, whether by accident or if the sedative is given permanently.
We cannot pretend that we do not perceive this part of suffering.
The patient, who will not be relieved of pain, will have more and more access to palliative sedatives.
Patients who are not given a sedative always say the same thing: "I want to die."
But that doesn’t necessarily mean “I want you to give me euthanasia,” it means “I want you to get rid of my pain.”
