The price of bitcoin first reached a maximum of $30 (23 euros) in June 2011, five months later it dropped to $2, today it is at the limit of about $10 (the list of rates is listed on bitcoincharts.com).
Compared to the world exchange for real money or financial products, this is nothing impressive.
And yet the European Central Bank (ECB) is interested in this fact in its report on virtual finance, which was released in October.
Bitcoin refers to “the most successful virtual money”, “competing the dollar and the euro” and “the like of ordinary money”.
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual money in that it is like “credits” used to process a video game that a person gets a game or can buy (and sometimes exchange back).
The social network Facebook has also developed a similar system.
Each month, however, the central authority monitors and processes individual communications.
In the case of Bitcoin, all the nodes of the network are depositors of books of ordinary accounts, controllers, issuers of money and buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
In fact, every transaction between two users takes place between two e-mail addresses by means of an e-mail.
However, the user can choose a different address for each payment, thus ensuring anonymity.
The information file associated with this transaction is electronically signed by a double-key encryption system.
This allows the network to verify the legitimacy of the transaction.
Thanks to the content of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the exchanged bitcoins exist in the public ledger of common accounts, which is distributed throughout the network.
The key phase is to write this new transaction into this book.
It takes place by solving a mathematical task given to computers, whose solver, a temporary central banker, will have the right to write this additional line.
This is a phase of cutting the file; i.e. transforming a huge file into a shorter and unique digital print.
Computers "take over" this new transaction and add a number to it, only then they "split" the whole.
The goal is to find a number that provides a specific print (a lot of zero at the beginning).
Once this number is found, the other nodes will easily check its correctness.
The transaction is then indestructibly displayed connected to the chain of all other transactions; any modification would change the footprint.
If the user wants to pay twice the same money very quickly (within ten minutes) for the purpose of fraud, the network will confirm only one of the two transactions - the second will be abandoned, because each of them has a different footprint.
The computer that solves the challenge will win 50 bitcoins.
In order to prevent inflation, this reward is regularly divided into two, probably by the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is thus limited by the number of 21 million, but they can be divided up to a hundred million, so the margin space here is...
The difficulty of the given task also increases with the increasing level of calculation.
The network has already experienced its ups and downs.
Websites that provide services for Bitcoin have been attacked and there has been a theft of stored bitcoins.
“The shell used is not about the protocol itself,” says Pierre Noizat, who founded Paymium, a real money payment company that uses the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also checks the possibilities of laundering dirty money thanks to this anonymous service.
But this problem also applies to cash.
Important players like Wikipedia reject the gifts of this nature.
Others, like the WordPress blogging platform, accept them.
Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron of the Weizman Institute in Israel recently analyzed a book of common accounts and showed that almost 80% of bitcoins are not circulating.
In November, "huge discounts" were launched.
“Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged,” says Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul to convert bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, who is also the author of the educational book on this money, has great confidence in the potential of this technology as a transactional network.
Its system, Paytunia, is equivalent to a credit card (with real money) or contactless mobile payment, but it uses the Bitcoin system to verify transactions that are cheaper as a result.
In addition, the holder manages his identity and can thus remain anonymous.
The system is easy to set up with merchants where there is no need to install new terminals or software.
It is enough to communicate an address that can be "photographed and recognized" by the phone, says Pierre Noizat, who assures that it already has thousands of users.
There is a general movement to question hierarchical systems and to move to more horizontal systems.
“Bitcoin will take a while to get established, but 2013 could be decisive,” he predicts.
In addition, the ECB’s report envisages a reassessment of the various risks that are now considered to be increased if this type of money is successful.
