Difficult Work on the Egyptian Constitution
President Muhammad Mursi has moved on to the next game of poker.
While Egypt remains the most divided in its history due to the proclamation of a constitution that temporarily grants it unlimited powers, it has decided to play the wacko.
On Wednesday, he announced, regardless of everyone else’s opinion, that the Constituent Assembly would approve the final text tomorrow.
Less than a week ago, the head of state gave the assembly another two months to complete the necessary work.
For almost two years, Egypt has been using a provisional text that has been supplemented many times, weakening the country’s constitutional stability and leading to legal disputes.
This new initiative further strengthened the country’s fragmentation.
From the point of view of the opposition, the president persists in his "autocratic delirium", continues to "violate his word" and "swindle the law".
Its supporters, however, say it is a means to reverse the constitutional and political crisis as quickly as possible and to speed up the transition process.
There will be a referendum in two weeks.
This is a very short period of time, which will force the Brotherhood to withdraw from the intention of the Egyptian text to clarify the article after the article.
For the president, it is also a way to regain national and democratic legitimacy, while the entire country is ousted by protests.
As confirmed in an interview with the American weekly Time, Muhammad Mursi seems to be convinced that the Egyptians will vote in favor.
Especially because this hastily organized vote puts the Egyptian people before the ultimatum: “Either you approve my text, or I will keep unlimited powers” that would otherwise have to end after the approval of the new constitution.
And in this special atmosphere yesterday, 85 members of the aforementioned Constituent Assembly with a large majority of Islamists approved the text.
Most of the Liberals were absent from the vote.
In mid-November, shortly before the announcement of the constitution, they slammed the door with the fact that they did not have the opportunity to assert their views.
Human rights defenders, civil society or members of religious minorities imitated their step.
In order to achieve a quorum, 11 substitutes were hastily added yesterday morning.
Some of them are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
It is not surprising then that articles of the Constitution were often voted unanimously.
The commentators further dwelled on the fact that one of the few disputes that day revolved around...the hours of prayer, when some committee members held the view that the hours in the meeting room were not properly arranged.
The text, which was voted on last night, consists of 234 articles.
The subject of general attention, Article 2, ultimately remains consistent with the 1971 version of the Constitution and provides that "the principles of Sharia law are the principal source of law".
Salafist parties, for which the introduction of Islamic law is one of the essential requirements, hoped to replace the term "principles" with the term "rules", which would allow for stricter enforcement.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been corrected is a sign of their goodwill and respect for other parts of Egyptian society.
"Criminalism," argues the liberals, who see in it only a speaking problem.
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution takes place through other articles.
They focus in particular on Article 220, which entrusts the University of Al-Azhar with an advisory role, in particular on matters relating to the verification of the conformity of laws with Sharia law.
According to Egypt expert Sophie Pommier, this is worrying because “persons called to express themselves are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
We can see the beginnings of the theocracy.”
Liberal concerns are further fuelled by the fact that the university’s next rector should be less moderate than the current one.
"So far, no specific religious consequences have been revealed.
With this constitution, Egypt remains a framework civil state.
Most of the lawyers who worked on this text are not Ulams, but university workers, many of them graduated from French schools," said Alexis Blouet, who is preparing the work on the constitutional transition in Egypt.
He agreed, however, that "there may be objections to the interpretation of Article 220, since the terms used therein belong to the religious dictionary.
In particular, there is a reference to "fiqh" [Islamic juridical science].
And in the future, the question may arise as to the extent to which civil judges are competent to express themselves.”
Yesterday's approved text is, in addition to religious sites, highly criticized for the extended powers it grants to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood insists that there has been a significant restriction on them compared to the former regime.
Another controversial place: the powers entrusted to the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the representatives of the army, the verification of the defense budget will not be carried out by the parliament, but by the National Defense Council.
In addition, civilian trials will not be prohibited in military courts, as demanded by the Association for the Protection of Human Rights.
These associations talk about their doubts in connection with the text, which they believe is directed against freedom.
The criminal act of blasphemy is maintained and insult is still prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, especially for the press.
Moreover, no article deals with the protection of women, emphasizes Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
In its view, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture referred to in Article 36.
This word was not mentioned in the previous constitution.
While the Egyptian president was scheduled to speak on television last night, demonstrations are scheduled for this afternoon.
The supporters of the head of state will then demonstrate on Saturday.
In Israel, Ukrainian tourists are waiting for holy places, the navel of the world and the sea from a saturated salt solution
The Promised Land combines the greatness of biblical truths, modern comfort and the untouched nature.
AaF has identified five of the most important reasons why you should visit Israel.
Worshiping the Holy Places
Visit the Jordan River, where Jesus was baptized.
It is claimed that all who enter this "bath" will receive God's mercy.
And Galilee - the place of Jesus' miracles: turning water into wine at a wedding, walking on water, calming the storm and filling the nets.
Here, too, Jesus appeared to his disciples and after the resurrection.
But the most holy places are in Jerusalem.
Believers here will walk through the Way of Pain or the Way of the Cross of Jesus (Latin: Via Dolorosa).
It begins at the fortress of Antonia - Pretoria - where the trial took place, passes through the streets of the Old Town and leads to the Temple of the Tomb of God on Mount Golgotha - to the place of crucifixion, to the stone of anointing and the place where Jesus was buried.
Here is the symbolic Christian navel of the world, which symbolizes the salvation of humanity.
And the monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem was built on the spot where, according to Christian legend, a tree grew from which they made a cross for the crucifixion of Jesus.
In Jerusalem there is also the most sacred place for Jews - the Wall of Tears, the rest of the temple, which was destroyed by the Romans in 70 AD.
According to tradition, people of different faiths leave notes with wishes, which are then fulfilled.
Taking the Road Vertically
The ruins of the fortress of Masada remained hidden from the enemy, which Herod the Great built in 25 B.C.E. for his family.
The ruin is located on the cliffs in the mountains at an altitude of 450 m above sea level.
Only those who are engaged in mountaineering can reach it by their own forces.
The others are taken by a cable car to this historic mountain.
And in the north of the country, at an altitude of 1600-2040 m, there is the well-known Hermon ski resort, which experiences a huge influx of tourists in the winter months.
This ski paradise is served by a shuttle bus from the foot of the hill.
The total length of the mountain slopes is 45 km.
According to ancient legend, pagan gods lived on the top of the mountain.
Visiting a unique museum
There are about 300 museums in this country.
You won’t be able to visit all of them in one trip.
But at least five of them, the most interesting, are definitely worth a visit.
Among them is the Israel Museum, which is located near the Knesset (parliament).
It contains ancient Kumran manuscripts or scrolls from the Dead Sea, which were found in the caves of the Judean desert, and about 500,000 archaeological and anthropological exhibits.
The Tel Aviv Museum of Art is also worth a visit.
His paintings are widely represented by Impressionists and Expressionists Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall, Picasso.
In Akkon you can visit the Al Basha museum-bathroom, which presents visitors with several rooms of ancient Turkish baths with figurines of bath users and spa nurses from that time.
In Caesarea, it is worth visiting the unique Ralli Private Museum, where you can admire the statues of Dali and Roden.
There are no guides or souvenir shops in the area.
Admission is free and donations are strictly refused.
The Fifth Museum – the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv – tells one of the most dramatic pages of history.
The most tragic part of the museum - the Children's Memorial - was built in memory of 1.5 million children who were murdered in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You will enter, and you will find yourself in total darkness.
The stars are shimmering.
And the names of the children of the Jews, and the names of the countries in which they died, are these.
Ukraine is also mentioned.
Improving your health
Israel’s three main spas are located on the shores of the Mediterranean, Red and Dead Seas.
All of them offer swimming pools, water parks, dolphinarium and oceanarium.
Interestingly, in the Red Sea you can also swim in the winter months, because the temperature of the water in it does not fall below 21 degrees Celsius and the air warms up to 23 degrees.
The dead sea is even warmer, and people bathe in it all year round.
The Dead Sea, by the way, is the most special sea in the world, located at the lowest point on the planet - at the level of 417 m below sea level.
The Azur water in it is a saturated salt solution that easily keeps on the surface even people who are not able to swim.
The surrounding landscape is unrealistically beautiful.
Go here to undergo treatment with the use of salt water - brine, and medicinal mud, which can treat health problems with dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, inflammation of the bronchi, diabetes, to cure the strangled nerves.
Touch the Mysterious Ancient Past
It is protected by the ancient part of Tel Aviv - the town of Jaffa on the Mediterranean coast.
They were crossed by a famous sea route connecting Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
Mentions of this city are found in the oldest Greek and Egyptian legends.
According to legend, this is the place where Noah built his ark and Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda, with whom they then lived a long and happy life together.
Tourists actually love the alleys with narrow alleys, named after the signs of the zodiac.
It is said that if you press against the walls in the alley of "your" sign, happiness will be favorably inclined to you.
In Jaffa, you may meet newlyweds who come here from all over Israel and even from other countries to get their picture taken.
And in Caesarea - in the city of King Herod - you can walk through the Roman theater and "conquer" the fortress of the crusaders.
In Roman times, Caesarea was the capital of Judea and the seat of Roman prosecutors, including Pontius Pilate.
Today, the carefully reconstructed theatre is used for evening concerts and opera performances.
Tourists, for a word
If you are going to Israel, you do not have to worry about your imperfect English: in this country, about 30% of the population speaks Russian.
On the way it is better to take money with you not in euros, but in dollars, which you can easily exchange for shekels (now 1 dollar is about 3.8 shekels).
Public transport is mainly buses, but there is a high-speed tram in Jerusalem and Haifa is the only metro line in the country with six stations that connects the lower city with the upper one.
It's basically an underground cable car.
Travelling by all types of public transport costs 6 shekels, for which you can drive 1.5 hours with a transfer.
In Israel, according to Jewish tradition, the Sabbath is celebrated on Saturday.
From Friday evening to sunset on Saturday, he stops working in markets, in shops and in public transport.
And Sunday morning starts the work week.
In many cafes, restaurants and hotels, you only get kosher food: except pork, seafood, shell-free fish and dishes that contain a combination of milk and meat.
They offer a large selection of dishes from lamb and beef, soups and desserts, prepared from coconut milk, traditional Jewish porridge hummus, various kinds of sauces, balls of minced oats - falafel, fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs on the streets of Israeli cities.
Therefore, there are a lot of well-fed cats who gracefully "travel according to their taste".
In the evening you can see them sleeping on the roofs of parked cars.
Transient cats love populated places and with taste they indulge in every kind of goodness.
