Plus insurance - $15 per day.
And to borrow a bike will cost about 15 shekels a day.
Museum tickets cost an average of 30 shekels.
Expressed Numbers
In 2012, more than three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel.
To know the country and rest came the most citizens of the USA, Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England and Ukraine.
From January to October 2012, 118.8 thousand Ukrainian tourists visited the Promised Land, which is 51% more than in the same period in 2010, before the cancellation of visas on February 9, 2011.
'Great and powerful' to announce it in Moscow: emigrants save money on language
While lawmakers and human rights defenders are still debating the law on mandatory language tests, fraudsters have already appeared in the country who sell “false” certificates.
Every year, 13 million foreign workers come to Moscow, St. Petersburg and other Russian cities.
Most of them are citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan, Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to make enough money to support families at home.
On December 1, the law came into effect, according to which every migrant worker will be required to pass the test of knowledge of the Russian language.
So far, this rule applies only to those who intend to work in the services sector, the housing and communal economy, lifestyle and retail.
However, the FMS promises that over time the relevant tests will be mandatory for all visitors.
However, the tests will consist not only of language skills, but also of Russian history and the fundamentals of law.
Knowledge of the language will also need to be confirmed in order to obtain and extend a work permit.
The exception applies only to citizens of countries where Russian is the official language.
This law is also not subject to people who have successfully achieved attestation and obtained an academic diploma until the collapse of the USSR in 1991.
Benefit, Conviction and Protection of Rights
The network of test sites will work under the auspices of the Pushkin Institute of the Russian Language, the University of Friendship among Nations, Moscow State University, St. Petersburg State University and other Russian universities.
Migrants can take tests in all cities; more than 160 such centres are already open in Russia.
The initiative to support the introduction of testing was also supported by the deputies of the State Duma and the FMS (Federal Migration Service).
But before the law came into force, human rights defenders were often able to ask the question in the press: what will it actually bring?
What will change the obligation to know the language for Russians and for the visitors themselves?
So, above all - the representatives of the migration service correspond - it will allow to reduce the number of people who suffer as a result of "slave labor."
Many people today talk about the protection of the rights of migrant workers, explains Chairman of the Board of FMS Russia in Tajikistan Viktor Sebelev.
The protection of their rights should begin before they leave.
Only the system of organized recruitment will allow 90% of the problems of foreign workers to be solved.
Problems arise in immigrants without a profession, without education, who do not know the language and do not have a medical examination.
Without knowledge of the language - he says with conviction Sebelev - the future migrant is condemned to clashes with dishonest people, who under the pretext of helping him provide a "command" to terrible, cramped accommodation, in which he and dozens of others, like himself, will spend days to 12 hours without food.
We receive a lot of complaints from our migrant workers.
"They promise them one thing in their homeland, but when they arrive, they will cheat them, they will seize their passports, they will not pay the promised wages," says MS Tolib <0xC5><0xA0>aripov, head of the main Tajik administration of labour migration.
Don't give up!
Nevertheless, many citizens of the Central Asian republics who intend to go to work in Russia, recognize that they not only do not know the language of the country they want to get into, but do not even have experience with the given work.
Of course, it is not their fault, but rather misfortune: very few Turkmen, Uzbeks, Tajiks can afford to get at least a reasonable basic education.
After all, their families also need something to feed their children, not to mention the fact that they need to be properly dressed, dressed and equipped for school.
As children reach a productive age, they have to go to work at the first opportunity.
Without knowledge of the language, it is difficult - they admit.
"You feel humiliated and inferior."
It is true that, with regard to the law on language tests, human rights defenders point to one important thing.
Testing will only be carried out on those migrants who have a legal status.
If they don’t have it, they won’t take exams or get any other official jobs.
Meanwhile, the majority of migrant workers are living in Russia illegally as before.
"Welcome, or Unauthorized Entry Banned"
Many of the incoming workers say that getting official status in our country is not easy.
The reason - bureaucratic obstacles and all those language difficulties.
In addition, legalization costs money: from 12 to 16 thousand rubles.
But a fake registration can be obtained quickly and only one and a half thousand.
Employees of the Russian police know that we basically have fake documents, without registration, and this leads to cases of blackmail.
"They demand a hundred, two for cigarettes, tea," - Umed Chuskadamov, a citizen of Tajikistan, told reporters about his experience.
"Come on, don't be greedy, buy yourself a painting"
On the first day of the language law, it was found that not only the documents of migrants about registration are fake.
FMS employees have already obtained several false certificates of passing the language test.
The falsified documents are printed on an ordinary colour printer.
Of course, they did not get to the new owners for free: each of the migrants, in the hope that they would thus facilitate the problem of passing the tests, paid for this document seven thousand rubles.
This is two and a half times more than the official test: it will cost migrant workers three thousand rubles.
The main task of the near future is to secure the system from corruption, so that workers cannot simply buy documents, both government officials and human rights defenders agree.
For now, the government can promise foreign workers who have failed the tests for the first time the time it takes for them to take a basic Russian language course.
For visitors who do not know Russian, it is assumed to work in areas where active interaction with people is not required.
