Poland and Space.
Last week, at a meeting of the European Space Agency’s country ministers, Poland was admitted as the 20th member of the European Space Agency as the second country from the former Eastern Bloc countries (after the Czech Republic, which became a full member of ESA on 12 November 2008).
Poland started working closely with ESA in 1994 and has been involved in a number of ESA projects over the years.
However, Poland’s journey into space began much earlier.
Polish enthusiasts devoted their flights to space even before World War II; but they did not always meet with understanding.
I recall, for example, A. <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld’s lecture at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory, which on 6 December 1933 presented ideas from his pioneering work Entry into Cosmonautics.
The ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left the listeners cold and after years <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934, <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld was awarded the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch Prize for the Entry into Cosmonautics in France.
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899-1966) later became a great promoter of astronomy and cosmonauts.
In Polish magazines he published hundreds of articles and wrote a number of books devoted to these scientific disciplines.
Gadomsky became a world-renowned promoter of cosmonautism, and his contribution was also rewarded by the fact that one of the craters on the far side of the Moon was named after him.
As early as 1925, a railway train was built in Poland, which was to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, the author of the proposal is not known and the details of the project are not known.
It is not even clear whether the missile should have been used to launch the dragnet or to brake it.
Information about this sweater is known only from the period press.
Since 1933, the Polish artillery began to engage in rocket fire.
The research was provided by the Armament Technology Cell in cooperation with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfk and Prof. Gustav Mokrzyckiegi.
From the preserved materials, it is clear that the research has reached the stage of practical tests.
However, with the arrival of German troops, the research was interrupted.
In 1937, a design of a photoelectric fighter rocket was published in the professional press, which was designed by the engineer Rohozinski, and the following year the work Rocket - air torpedo and aerial missile bomb by the author Leliwy-Krzywoblocky was published.
Both projects were designed for military use of rocket engines.
Just before the war, the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy) was responsible for all projects for the military use of rocket technology, which coordinated all work.
The Committee was founded in 1937, but after two years of activity, its work ended with the start of the war.
Other works on cosmonautism appear in the Polish press after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Astronautical Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time there is a mention of the company in the November 1954 issue of the journal Problems, in which there are four more extensive articles devoted to astronautics.
In one of them, from Prof. M. Subotowicze, it is proposed to create a society that will deal with cosmonauts.
At that time, artificial satellite projects were already underway, and it was clear that space research was a promising field.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronautical Society (PTA) has been trying to join the International Astronautical Federation (founded in 1951) and in the autumn of this year PTA became a full member.
In the following year, the first president of the PTA Kazimierz Zaraniewicz (1902–1959) became the vice-president of the International Astronautical Federation.
He held this position until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the PTA has played a significant role in the development of the highly successful RM (Meteorological Rocket) rocket, which became the first Polish rocket to conduct scientific research.
The first type of RM-1 was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
The rocket with an access of 1800 meters was about 80 cm long and its weight was less than 5 kg.
Later, an improved version of the RM-1A was built, and in the summer of 1959, two-stage flight tests of the RM-2 rocket were launched in the Bled desert.
The rocket was 1.4 meters long and its weight was about 11.5 kg.
Another development type was already supposed to be capable of real scientific work - the RM-34 rocket was supposed to have access to 14.5 km and its task was to monitor the high-altitude wind.
However, in 1962, further development was suspended.
The successor to the first RM rockets was the Meteor-1 rocket developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage rocket, its total length was 510 cm and the launch weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types (designated Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed, which differed in the size of the space for scientific instruments.
In the Meteor-1A rocket, space was available with a volume of 0.4 liters, Meteor-1B with a volume of 0.34 liters and Meteor-1C with a volume of 0.62 liters.
The maximum access for all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Aeronautical Institute developed the Meteor-2 rocket, the first flight tests of which began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had a launch weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a payload of 10 kg to a height of about 60 km.
Later versions of Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 were built.
Poland joined the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and formed the COSPAR National Committee two years later.
In 1978, Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remko to be involved in space exploration on Soviet artificial satellites.
Repeal of the Public Works Act is not a solution.
Last week, the Constitutional Court overturned the Public Works Act.
The resolution sparked a lively debate in the public.
It will certainly be interesting to look at this issue from a broader perspective.
Liberally oriented economic systems in the EU as well as in the globalised world are based on the principle of more, unregulated economic competition.
In its effect, this means that individual economic units, national economic systems, are in permanent conflict with each other.
The cause is the principle of free trade and the free, unfettered movement of private capital, together with gratuitous financial speculation.
Due to significant differences in the price of labor, (wage) there is a price tension.
By this term it is necessary to understand the situation in which the producer tries to compete by importing cheap goods by "subduing" the price of the competitor in order to extract a larger share of the market and thereby increase its own profits.
On a mass scale, this means for most entrepreneurs either to shift production abroad, or there to buy cheaply, or to disappear.The result is high unemployment in countries where labor prices are high compared to other economies.
Since private capital has no social responsibility and thus no responsibility for the unemployment it produces, the social expenditure of the state necessarily increases.
The whole situation is reinforced by the absolute reluctance of the masters of business to pay taxes and thereby compensate for the economic and social damage he has caused to society in his pursuit of profit.
The situation is so well known that it is not necessary to provide specific statistics.
The ruthless practices of private capital create in individual economies a situation in which the governments of individual countries are forced to enter into competition with each other in order to artificially reduce the social level of their own population in order to attract foreign capital to the country.
In other words, governments are giving private capital its own population, regardless of social decline.
This is especially evident in the changes in the laws in force.
The aim is to economically force its own population to accept the price dictation of private capital, especially in the field of wages.
This is done both by the system of economic coercion in the case of long-term unemployment, and by limiting the rights of employees in the field of labour law.
The result is growing poverty along with increasing disparities between the poor and the rich.
In the SRN, there have been many years of public food outlets for the poor, who cannot do their own work.
The number of these people is already in the millions.
In the context of increasing the competitiveness of the German economy, it is quite common for people who are properly employed to receive such a salary that they have to be remunerated to an existential minimum.
