In a world of constant connection, it's not so bad to be bored
The last Thanksgiving I unexpectedly spent five hours at the airport when our plane was having mechanical difficulties and we had to wait for the arrival of another plane.
So we had a lot of time to think about boredom.
I won't lie to you.
Waiting half a day at the airport for the next flight is pretty annoying, despite the distractions of books, magazines and iPhones (not to mention duty-free shops).
But some scientists and experts on child development are increasingly coming up with praise of boredom.
They say it’s good for us (and our kids) to get bored sometimes.
It forces the brain to go in interesting directions, which can promote creativity.
And since most of us are constantly connected to a screen these days, we don’t have a chance to enjoy the boredom.
Should we support boredom?
Oh, yeah.
Oh, no.
But I'll come back to that.
First, like many people, I assumed that boredom is a relatively new phenomenon that occurred with the advent of more leisure time.
But as Peter Toohey, a professor of Greek and Roman history at the University of Calgary in Canada, says, he is the author of Boredom: A Lively History (Yale University Press, 2011).
"In fact, boredom has a long history," he said.
On the walls of Pompeii was found a Latin inscription concerning boredom, dating from the first century AD.
And then there is the question of how we define boredom.
The problem is that it has been defined and discussed in many different ways, said John D. Eastwood, a professor of psychology at York University in Ontario, Canada.
After reviewing the research literature and presenting the idea to a target group of about 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues defined boredom as an experience “I wanted to do something that would satisfy me, but I wasn’t able to.”
Boring differs from apathy in that a person is not involved in anything, but wants to be.
He says that in apathy there is no need to do anything.
He says that the core of boredom is “violation of the process of attention, associated with a bad mood and a sense of slow running time.”
Boring can be very similar to depression.
But Professor Eastwood said that while they may have a relationship with each other, bored people tend to see the problem as an environment or world, while people who are depressed see the problem in themselves.
Sometimes we think we’re bored when we’re just having trouble concentrating.
In his study "The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention", published in the journal Perspectives on Psychological Science in September, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues pointed to an earlier experiment in which participants listened to a tape in which a person read an article from the journal.
Some groups heard a loud and unrelated television program in the next room, others heard it so quietly that they barely noticed it, while the third group did not hear it at all.
Those who heard the TV show silently reported more boredom than the other two groups - they had trouble concentrating, but were not sure why, and attributed these troubles to boredom.
When you’re trying to focus on a difficult or engaging task, a distraction can lead to boredom, said Mark J. Fenske, a professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph in Ontario and one of the study’s authors.
On the other hand, when you’re doing something boring, “like finding the wrong parts on the factory line, distracting music can help keep you from getting bored.”
In fact, he said, we now know that twisting and dabbing, which is often seen as a sign of boredom, can actually help fight boredom and keep people physically more alert.
“The research shows that children who are allowed to spin learn more and retain more information than those who are forced to sit still,” said Professor Fenske.
We’ve all experienced boredom at times – the delay of my flight, the buzzing speaker, especially the long film.
Some people are more likely to get bored than others.
To help measure boredom, scientists developed the Boredom Proneness Scale in the 1980s.
The scale includes questions such as: "Many things I have to do are repetitive and monotonous," and "I have so many interests that I don't have time to do them all."
Using these scales, scientists found that boys tend to get bored more often than girls, said Stephen Vodanovich, a professor of psychology at the University of West Florida, especially when it comes to the need to have more and different external stimulations.
Teenagers, however, are generally incompetent.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of human and social development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted nearly 400 teenagers and their parents seven to eight times a day.
He found that 32 percent of teens reported being bored in school and doing homework, while 23 percent reported being bored when they were not at school.
On the other hand, 3 percent of parents said they were bored.
Professor Larson said he did not know whether the percentage of boredom would be now, 21 years later, higher or lower.
But he said he knows that “adultery is a prime time for boredom,” which is largely due to the fact that children and young people are not given much control over what they want to do.
So back to my original question: “Is boredom good for you?”.
As research shows, sometimes not, because in its extreme form it can lead people to take absurd physical risks, play gambling games, or abuse addictive substances as a way to mitigate it.
On the other hand, many philosophers and writers discussed the connection between boredom and creativity, said Professor Vodanovich, who has studied the problem for more than two decades.
“Burning is a brain’s way of telling you that you should do something else,” said Gary Marcus, a professor of psychology at NYU.
But the brain doesn't always know the most appropriate thing to do.
If you get bored and use this energy to play guitar and cook, it will make you happy.
However, if you watch TV, it will only make you happy for a while, not in the long run.
So if your child gets bored and you give him an iPad, he won’t get bored anymore, but he won’t learn how to have fun or drive independently, Professor Fenske said.
And "this separate management is transferred from one situation to another," the professor said.
Your child will not only learn how to entertain themselves, but will gain greater self-control in other areas.
I don't think we really want to celebrate boredom.
But we shouldn't be too critical of her either.
Our goal should rather be to feel comfortable when we are out of reach of the constant throttling of activity and technology.
Professor Eastwood agreed.
"We blame her for the need to get bored even more, but the boredom is a painful, restless desire to be connected to something meaningful," he said.
What people are actually looking for, he said, is a way to relax and enjoy your free time.
"In an environment where we're constantly overstimulated," he said, "it's hard to find ways to have fun when the noise goes off."
In Colorado, there is no guide to the new marijuana law.
Nineteen-year-old Anthony Orozco, a college student and footballer from southeastern Colorado, faces criminal charges for something that will soon be legal across the state - for holding a few grams of marijuana and the pipe he used to smoke it.
Mr. Orozco said that one September day he was driving with several friends in Lamar, on the plains near the Kansas border, when he was stopped.
