In the uncertain weeks following the Colorado vote on legalizing a small amount of marijuana for recreational use, the response of hundreds of smaller drug cases depends on the location rather than the law.
Hundreds of cases of marijuana-related offenses have already been canceled here and in Washington state, which has approved similar measures.
The police department has stopped charging adults aged 21 and older with possession of a small amount that will be legally allowed after the law enters into force in the coming weeks.
But plaintiffs in more conservative Colorado counties have said they will continue to pursue existing marijuana-related cases, and are still accusing people of possession.
At the same time, several cities from the suburbs of Denver toward the western mountains are voting to prevent the opening of new, state-licensed marijuana shops in their municipalities.
"This thing is developing so fast that I don't know what's going to happen next," said Daniel J. Oates, a police chief in the city of Aurora, east of Denver.
Regulators in the state of Washington are also shaking their heads.
And they are looking for instructions on how to set up a licensing system for cultivation, production, distribution and sale - all by the date of December 1, 2013.
They say Colorado, for better or for worse, is ahead of most states in regulating marijuana, first for medical use, and now for recreational use.
"Colorado has a more regulated market, so it's going to be a good guide," said Brian E. Smith, a spokesman for the state's liquor licensing board.
But as Mr. Smith has admitted, no place or system can do more than suggest what might work.
"There is no real precedent by which we could be guided," he said.
The Washington law, known as I-502, takes effect on December 6, which also leaves an annual vacuum during which the state licensing system will not yet exist, but legal ownership does.
And there are hellish mechanical issues that need to be resolved during this time, such as how to balance a state directive regarding "appropriate access" to licensed marijuana with its ban on the trade of cannabis within 330 meters of schools, parks, playgrounds or children's centers.
“Nowhere will it be more difficult to place a licensed cannabis trade than in urban areas, especially in the metropolitan area of Seattle,” said Ben Livingston, a spokesman for the Center for Legal Cannabis, a recently founded research group.
On November 21, police chief Oates of the City of Aurora sent an email to his officers informing them that the city prosecutor would no longer prosecute crimes involving possession of small amounts of marijuana by every citizen over the age of 21 and that the police would “immediately” stop charging people with these crimes.
Chief Oates said police will enforce city laws regulating medical marijuana growers and will continue to prosecute drug dealers and dealers.
In Weld County, North Colorado, District Attorney Ken Buck has a tougher view.
After the vote, he said his office would continue to prosecute marijuana possession cases, mostly as a way to pressure users to seek treatment.
Currently, 119 people are facing charges of possession of 56 grams or less of marijuana, although many of them face further charges.
"Our office is obliged to prosecute criminal offenses that were criminal offences at the time they occurred," Buck said in a statement.
The response was also complicated in places such as the rural Mesa district, where voters rejected the marijuana initiative.
Police in Grand Junction, the county's largest city, are no longer accusing adults of holding small amounts.
District Attorney Pete Hautzinger supports this decision, but has also decided not to dismiss all ongoing cases of possession.
"I don't think I'm wasting my time continuing to enforce the law until it changes," he said.
Although 55 percent of Colorado voters supported the measure, bringing recreational marijuana into the hands of the government and the legal system will never be easy.
And contradictory reactions across the state have revealed a deep rift among local officials in light of this large-scale state-green experiment.
For district attorneys, this is a “cultural barrier,” said Sean McAllister, a Denver lawyer representing marijuana defendants, and a local spokesman for the National Organization for Marijuana Law Reform.
“They’ve spent so much of their lives prosecuting people that they still can’t really accept that it’s legal,” he said.
As the first states to treat small amounts of marijuana as alcohol, Colorado and Washington are on their way to becoming national drug legalization test cases.
Advocates and state authorities are planning new boundaries for legalized sales while also anxiously awaiting instructions from the federal government, which still plans to consider the sale and cultivation of marijuana as federal crimes.
Advocates of legalizing marijuana hope the Justice Department will comply.
Despite several arrests of medical marijuana sellers and patients who use it that have attracted attention, the federal government has mostly left medical marijuana deals in Colorado, Washington, and 16 other states in operation.
While anti-drug agents are unlikely to go out the door to catch a small bag of drugs, they are likely to resist allowing state-regulated recreational marijuana trades allowed by new laws, said Kevin A. Sabet, a former adviser on anti-drug policy to the president’s administration.
Several Colorado cities are not waiting for the progress of the federal authorities.
Even before the election day, some local governments have approved a moratorium on any new marijuana trades, although it will take about a year before any trade can open.
Last week, the city of Montrose in the west of the state proposed a six-month ban and is likely to come into force next week.
“We don’t want to be in a situation where we give someone a license and then we’re going to have a big federal issue,” said Bob Nicholson, a city council member.
Our municipality voted against this addendum.
We are looking at what the municipality voted for, versus what the state voted for.
