Petronella Wyatt: "I was forced to leave Oxford because I'm a conservative."
Today’s university students are not the only ones being attacked for their opinions.
I don't remember ever dreaming of studying at Oxford University.
Both my father and my older brother studied at a university that I thought was the world’s largest seat of knowledge, a modern-day wrapped Greek symposium motivating two pillars of civilization, free thinking and tolerance.
And so far in the late 1980s, within two weeks of attending Worcester College, where I wanted to study history, I packed my suitcases and rushed into the first scandal of my life.
My father collapsed and cried.
My friends were confused.
The Evening Standard claimed that I gave it up because I objected to loving students in the side room.
Writer A. N. Wilson declared that I had left because I had been forced to drink from stale cups.
The truth was less comical.
I ran away.
Yes, I escaped because I was subjected to systematic bullying and intimidation.
Not because of my rather bizarre name or the fact that I came from a private school.
I was persecuted for one reason and in this cradle of supposed enlightenment it was both bigoted and barbaric: my father, the late Woodrow Wyatt, was a high-ranking adviser to Margaret Thatcher and I was a supporter of the Conservative Party.
You may be asking why I'm pulling this off right now.
Just because the latest news suggests that a new generation of students on the right have suffered similar persecution since Wednesday.
The institutionalised and growing hatred of conservative students at Oxford is so great that last week a group of these students demanded the same protection of equal rights as gays, people with disabilities and ethnic minorities.
Conservative members of the Corpus Christi College Junior Association (JCR) claim that because of their political views, they are “often actively isolated, exposed to personal attacks, and made to appear unwelcome.”
They ask for the creation of a position on the University Committee for Equal Opportunities, which would ensure that their views can be freely communicated.
Their situation was not helped by the recent BBC Two documentary, Wonderland: Young, Bright and on the Right, about a student political event that the conservatives described as bizarre and neo-Nazi.
The show featured graduate Joe Cooke, a former president of the Oxford University Conservative Association (OUCA), who rode the Rolls-Royce, was dressed in a silver suit and had a stick with a silver head.
At other universities, conservative students say that because of the introduction of higher education, they are treated as "victim lambs".
Twenty-year-old Luke Black, vice president of the Nottingham University Conservative Association, told the Sunday newspaper that "leftist influence in universities is growing.
People think we're like the Bullingdon Club without even meeting us."
Twenty-one-year-old Corpus Christi history student Samuel Roberts, who is behind the movement for greater protection, says such a climate is “unpleasant,” while nineteen-year-old elected OUCA president Stephanie Cherill says there has been a deterioration in the JCR’s right-of-centre approach to people.
“This poses a threat to the atmosphere of intellectual discussion, as well as to the good living conditions of members,” he says.
During my first few weeks in Oxford, I was a minority by one member.
I joined in September 1986, 18 years old and stunningly shy.
Hatred of the Conservative Party was the most intense.
A year earlier, the university had voted against granting the honorary degree to former student Margaret Thatcher due to cuts in funding for higher education.
From the atmosphere, even the Stalinists would tremble with fear.
During the first few days of the introductory week, when new students are meeting with each other and with professors, I got to taste the pollen that was supposed to come.
I have found that not only do the professors silently approve the labeling of conservative pupils, but they are also willing to take part in it.
The policy of mining strike, privatization and resistance of the government to the sanctions against apartheid in the South African Republic was introduced into the wood-clad listeners.
My first lecture concerned the translation of the French text from the 18th century into English, and I was not prepared for what followed.
"Miss Wyatt," said Professor Harry Pitt (now deceased), "please translate the first paragraph."
I've had enough of this.
Professor Pitt, a little man with a cake-like face, was very gallant.
"Thatchers refuse to learn French, or are they just stupid?" he asked.
The other students nodded.
There were tears in my eyes.
"I suggest that you take some basic French lessons in your spare time, if you're not too busy with social issues," Professor Pitt said.
I was crushed and returned to my room.
I was sitting alone at dinner at school when I felt a slight tap on my shoulder.
He was a second-year student named James, who introduced himself as a member of OUCA.
"I know who you are," he said gently.
Unfortunately, that's the way it is.
Anyone suspected of conservatism is a target.
It's bad enough for me, but they know your father's close to Margaret Thatcher, so it's gonna be even worse for you.
Most of the conservatives pretend to be Labourers.
Later, at the local pub, I tried to pretend in a cowardly way.
I insisted that I disagree with everything Thatcher said.
This trick proved to be a failure.
A student of the first year of philosophy, politics and economics, who (what an irony) went to Eton, said: “You are the daughter of a fascist pig.”
You're infected.
The other students took notes with him.
I was twisted, dirty.
"How do conservatives love each other?" one asked.
They beat each other, don't they?
I felt the way homosexuals must have felt before the liberal legislation of the 1960s.
Could I ever lead a normal life at Oxford?
Would I be forced to meet with like-minded people only after dark?
Would I have to turn into a Labour and suppress my natural inclinations?
Three years have unfolded before me as a purveyor of ignorance and isolation.
The only openly conservative professor was Norman Stone, a professor of modern history who was based at my faculty.
He was hated not only for being conservative, but also for being Margaret Thatcher’s foreign policy adviser and one of those who wrote speeches to her.
He was almost there.
He hated the place for its provinciality and smallness, and for its tendency towards a Marxist-deterministic view of history.
In 1997 he became a professor at Bilkent University in Ankara, Turkey.
"You won't be happy here," he said.
I began to move from Oxford to my parents’ house in London, seeking refuge with my uninvolved metropolitan friends and family.
I told my father I hated Oxford and why.
He couldn't believe it.
During his studies at Oxford in the 1940s, all political views were accepted.
"But it's the best place in the world," he said pathetically.
They wouldn't do that, not in a city of dreams.
Even my communist friends have always had perfect manners.
His wet eyes grinned.
Try it again.
I'm sure it's just a joke.
It would break my heart if you left.
Exhausted by frequent trips to London, my emotional resilience worsened.
My friend, also a supporter of the Conservative Party, succumbed to the pressure and gave up his conviction.
The following week, during the course of teaching, when another professor of history declared in all seriousness that I was the "enemy of the people", I decided to do the same.
Even as I blushed inside, I admitted that my "parents brainwashed me" and called them "old fools."
The relief was only short-lived.
The nail in the coffin of my Oxford career was beaten by my father.
At that time, he wrote two columns in Murdoch's paper every week.
My door was locked.
I shrugged inside, and after five minutes my pursuers gave up.
When they left, I packed my suitcase and caught the first train to London.
I never came back.
You can call me a crippled weakling.
But no 18-year-old girl or boy should be subjected to such intimidation and poisoning in an educational institution.
Even more tragic, however, is that it was Oxford, from which not only 14 conservative prime ministers emerged, but which to this day also hides behind the undeserved reputation of a place with equality and freedom of thought.
