The hardest craft in the world: sulfur carriers in the area of the Kawah Ijen volcano
For four euros, carriers in the area of the Indonesian volcano gamble with their lives and health when they carry 70 kilos of sulfur down steep stone paths.
There are people for whom their work is hell, and there are those who literally work in hell.
This is the case of Anta Wijayi, one of 400 miners who make a living by mining sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano in the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
Because of this, every day it has to rumble to the bottom of the crater, where sulfur gases escape from the inside of the Earth and when in contact with the air it passes into a solid state.
After cutting out large blocks of sulfur, which together weigh up to 70 kilos, he carries them on his shoulder in two bamboo baskets along crisp stone paths.
To the summit of the volcano, which stands 2,386 meters, it is only 250 meters, but it takes the exhausted carriers more than 40 minutes to climb up at a tortoise pace, because they maintain balance and carefully consider their steps, so as not to slip and fall into the abyss.
They know that any trip could become a life, as happened to one French tourist who fell from the rocks of Kawah Ijen years ago.
Miners in Kawah Ijen earn five cents for every kilo of sulfur they extract
When they are up, they make their way around tourists who photograph them as if they were monkeys in a circus, and tirelessly carry heavy baskets to the weight that the mining company placed a little lower, at an altitude of 1850 meters.
It is a company PT Candi Ngrimbi, which has been profiting in the volcano since 1960 and has never paid its workers more than 662 Indonesian rupees (five cents) per kilo of sulfur.
It is then sold for 10,000 rupees (83 cents) to the petrochemical industry, as this mineral has its place in everyday life and is used for the production of matches, fun pyrotechnics, cosmetics, dynamite and even for bleaching sugar.
"Because it normally carries 70 kilos, we will earn about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) for each trip," explains Anto, who usually takes three trips a day.
One trip takes him three hours and at the end he is destroyed, but he can earn 138,000 rupees (11.5 euros) per day.
Even if it seems like a negligible amount for such an inhuman effort, it is three times what he would earn in the field.
"The daily wage of miners is very high here. For example, for collecting coffee, 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) per day is paid and the salary for fourteen days is two million rupees (167 euros), "explains the carrier, who previously worked on the tourist island of Bali as a mason.
There his salary was 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) a day and the work was not so hard, but Anto returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a village near the volcano, for a serious reason, which is as convincing as sulfur in Indonesia: "I married a young girl from Bali, who is a Hindu."
Anto has asthma, he's not breathing well, he's still coughing and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases
At the age of 27, Anto risks his life three times a day in the Kawah Ijen volcano, whose sulfur has already begun to collect its tax on him, even though his face is protected by a special mask and glasses.
He has asthma, he's breathing badly, he's still coughing, and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases escaping from the volcano.
This is the price he has to pay to achieve his dream.
“I’m going to work for two more years because I want to open a business or study Spanish or French,” he promises in more than decent English.
This sympathetic and intelligent young man caught in fate could be a tour guide, waiter or receptionist at the hotel, and instead does the job of a porter.
It shares a dirty wooden hut with other carriers and wakes up every day at two o'clock in the morning, because sulfur does not stop boiling at night and its characteristic yellow color changes to blue and glows in the dark.
Despite the surrounding darkness, Anto goes into the crater and illuminates the path with a small flashlight, which is attached to the helmet and he bought it for his own money.
About 400 carriers carry a basket of sulfur from the bottom of the crater on their shoulders
Although the company has a high income, it has not mechanized the extraction of sulfur due to cost savings, nor does it provide any equipment to the carriers working on their own and with such effort.
In fact, they do not even get a share of 30,000 rupees (2.5 euros) from the photography surcharge, which, along with a ticket for 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros), is chosen by the park rangers from tourists who come to photograph the volcano and its human mussels.
"This work is for livestock, not people," says Madrusin, a 42-year-old hard-working supporter who has been working in Kawah Ijen for three decades since he left school.
He is able to lift up to 110 kilos and assures us that he will be able to work "as long as he can" because he needs money to educate his three sons between the ages of 18 and 10.
I'm not going to retire, I'm going to die here because the volcano has been my whole life
Although sulfur burns the throat and stings in the eyes, when the wind unexpectedly turns and catches the miners in the dense fumes that come out of the volcano, the miners are so assertive that none of them complains that they suffer from serious diseases... but this is evident from their frequent sores of the respiratory system.
Unainik, who balances his basket on his back, can weigh only 50 kilos at the age of 53.
Every day he and his colleagues mine 15 tons of sulfur in a volcano, which then three trucks take a steep path between the cisterns to a warehouse in Tamansari, 18 kilometers away.
"I'm not going to retire, I'm going to die here because the volcano has been my whole life," Unainik says, opening a wide mouth that lacks several teeth.
Of his five sons, the oldest, thirty-year-old, also earns by mining sulfur.
Time is running out, but the constant misery of one of the world’s most difficult crafts persists from generation to generation – crafts performed by human mule in Kawah Ilyen.
Singapore is looking for a baby to save the economy
Singaporeans cheat that they don’t have children, on career, stress and the cost of living and education.
"The population of Singapore needs to grow."
I am married and I am a patriot, you are my wife and you are a patriot. Let's fulfill our civic duty and give birth to a new life!
It may seem incredible that this slogan is part of a menthol candy ad, but yet – or perhaps that’s why – the video was massively extended to YouTube earlier this year in Singapore.
These sentences are part of a rap that uses local phrases such as "let's put a bow in the oven" as a mockery of the birth rate in Singapore.
The advertising agency BBH, which created the video, hopes that with this advertisement they will be able to point out the problem in a funny way.
Douglas Hamilton, the agency’s artistic director, said he wanted to use the influence of music to help people fulfill “their civic duty.”
“It’s all about the internet, so it had to be fun and funny.
This is the biggest problem in this country.
We are the worst in the world in the reproduction of our population, so we felt it was a topic that we had to touch.
We knew that the government was trying to do a lot of things like spread perfumes with pheromones or organize dating parties.
Many of these ideas may have been creative, but not entirely functional.
So we thought, why not do the most creative thing possible, like the composition of the rap, to solve this problem."
1.2 children
The one who does not take it lightly is the Singaporean government.
They will spend $1,300 per year to encourage citizens to have more children.
The government’s marriage and family package provides up to $15,000 per child, extends maternity leave, and allocates financial benefits.
All of these measures had little effect.
Singapore is a wealthy city-state with advanced technology in Southeast Asia, also known for the conservatism of its representatives and strict social controls.
The birth rate in Singapore in terms of population ranking is currently 1.2 children per woman.
The last time the birth rate exceeded the value of 2, which is considered a recovery rate, in 1976.
Why don’t Singaporeans have more children?
Tan Wei Ming, director of the National Population Office’s marriage and family department, says it’s because of “better education” and “a wider range of career opportunities.”
“People thus have a wider range of options when it comes to life goals and priorities, it’s not just marriage and family,” he explains.
These changes in social norms have contributed to an increase in the number of free people and to the postponement of marriage and childbirth, resulting in a reduction in the birth rate in Singapore.
While there have been attempts to drastically increase the influx of immigrants as a measure against a decline in the population, this has caused resentment among the local population.
On some Singaporean websites, there is an undisguised xenophobia against many new immigrants, especially Chinese, who are criticized for maintaining low wages and little effort to integrate.
The increase in immigration is also seen as one of the reasons why Singapore’s ruling party recorded its worst election result since independence last year.
After the elections, there was an attempt to solve the problem using quotas and higher fees for foreign workers.
Unexpected consequences
While the decline in the birth rate has a known impact on national economic growth, tax revenues, health spending and immigration policy, there have also been some unexpected consequences for Singapore.
The government is trying not to build so many small houses.
For example, it began to influence the real estate business.
The Office for Urban Development began regulating the number of small apartments known as "boot boxes" that can be built in certain urban zones.
These apartments have an area of 46 square meters and have had great success in sales.
However, there is concern that these apartments may promote a youthful lifestyle and discourage developers from building large family homes.
But Lim Yew Soon, CEO of developer EL Developers, claims that their “boot boxes” sell far faster than larger homes.
“They are more popular, selling days to weeks faster than houses with a larger area.
That’s why they’re so much better for our money flow.”
However, they admit that the new standards set clearer rules for developers who were previously limited when they wanted to offer too many small houses in a single project.
Too stressed out
Singapore is a city-state.
While these new rules could be aimed at raising the nation’s birth rate, an interview with Singaporeans working in a financial district in the city centre suggests they won’t have much of an effect.
“People are still under stress, houses are expensive, as is education, which is why a lot of people put it off,” says the young official.
"Let others have children.
But for me it’s important to rely on my own money and time,” says another, about 20 years old, young man.
Men and women refer to careers, stress, and the cost of living and education as reasons that prevent them from having children.
So no matter how much the government tries to force citizens to have children, it is Singaporeans who have the final say about starting a family.
What's private offline is private and online
Privacy.
According to a dictionary published by the Royal Spanish Academy, it is something that has a personal nature or "an area of private life that everyone has the right to protect against any violation".
What is privacy for a person under the age of 16?
How does he apply this definition in his daily life and on social networks?
Does he understand the danger he is exposed to when he publishes things on the Internet that he would certainly not tell anyone in ordinary communication?
Journalists from elPeri<0xC3><0xB3>dico interviewed five boys and girls between the ages of 10 and 15 who are frequent Internet users.
In four cases, they considered the concept of privacy to be “something entirely of their own” on a personal level and as a “user name and password” when it came to social media.
“I wouldn’t reveal my biggest secret,” Jorge, 10, said in an effort to explain the importance of privacy in places like Facebook, Twitter, Hotmail and Windows Live Messenger, where he has had accounts for two years.
"They're very secretive, my mom may know about them, but not the whole world," she says.
"I'm putting some nice pictures on FB, or pictures of how we play.
I also talk to friends there.
I wouldn’t share a picture that wasn’t mine, or a picture that would make someone laugh,” he says.
This boy realizes that it is wrong to publish obscene photographs, photographs of naked persons or photographs of crimes, or to write derogatory or rude comments.
Jorge says he knows all 35 friends he has on FB and his nine fans on Twitter.
Most of them are relatives.
Among them is a mother who has the name and password of one of the accounts.
"I have set up a Twitter account so that I can express my views and write interesting posts.
I don’t know if anyone will answer me, I just put them there,” he adds.
“Social media is fun, I can talk to relatives who are far away or communicate quickly with friends,” he says.
Without hesitation, he says he would never accept a request from an unknown person.
He wouldn't even care if someone recommended him to someone he didn't know.
The case of 14-year-old Jose is different.
This teenager owns accounts on Hotmail, Facebook, My Space and Ask networks and on the last mentioned network admits that he does not know 20 people from his list of friends.
"I'm not afraid of it because we have something in common, like music," he says.
According to this boy, none of them told him anything, nor did he ask for his address or phone number.
"If they insisted on me or demanded it from me, I would simply remove them from my account," he admits.
José signed up for Ask after reading the recommendations on Twitter.
These guys are not strangers to what is now called cyberbullying.
"A well-known friend has been blackmailed on social media.
They threatened him and demanded money.
He never knew who it was," he said.
According to José, the victim did not log out of the account.
"She just activated her private mode."
Then it explains a series of steps to set up your account safely.
Unlike Jorge, this boy would publish photos of acquaintances in unpleasant or embarrassing situations.
"Of course I would if someone bothered me or I just wanted to.
“I know it’s cyberbullying,” he said.
Key questions
Marielos Porrasov<0xC3><0xA1>, a teacher of English and a graduate of the field of Education and Teaching, believes that in order for children and adolescents in social networks to be properly oriented, they must understand that the main goal of these networks is to inform them.
He states that: "The Internet was created as a means of seeking information, but when social networks appeared, the rules of the game changed."
Marrielos Porrasov<0xC3><0xA1> notes that academician Marc Prensky, a graduate of pedagogy at Yale University and author of the article Digital Natives and Digital Immigrants, introduced these concepts to explain this phenomenon.
“Digital natives are children and young people who were born at the time of this technology.
We are digital immigrants who have to teach them, and yet we are just learning,” he says.
He explains that this is a complex topic, "because we ask them to recognize what is appropriate to spread, publish and say, and what is not, at an age when they are not yet mature".
Also, to be considerate – as far as the surroundings are concerned – at a time when what they most want is to be liked, to have thousands of friends and not to think about the consequences.”
According to this specialist, the most effective way for children and adolescents to show what privacy is, is to ask questions that make them think.
"Telling them not to do something doesn't work," he adds.
Marrielos Porrasov<0xC3><0xA1> also mentions some of the possibilities: There are things you wouldn’t tell a stranger, so why are you doing it on the Internet?
Or: Would you like someone to publish your photo the way you published your friend?
Do you know what others are posting about you?
When you're tagging the people in the pictures from the celebrations, did you ask those people for permission?
And one more thing: Do they always need to know what you’re doing?
Another point is to realize that they have to behave in the environment of the Internet as well as outside it.
They're the same rules.
“A person outside the internet is governed by respect, morality, and other principles, and the same should be true on social media,” he says.
Supervision
Estuardo Guardia, a university professor, a first-degree teacher and an educational counselor explains that it is necessary for parents of children to carefully read the rules of social networks.
“If they understand any kind of fraud, they have a good basis to talk to their children about the consequences of setting up an online account.
For example, with regard to age or what is allowed to be shared or published," he says.
The Guardia is of the opinion that it is crucial to remind children of the traditional rule of "don't talk to strangers".
