Fabrizi was 21 years old when his test result was confirmed: HIV positive.
"It was as if lightning had struck me," he recounts, recalling a moment of truth the doctor was trying to "slightly mitigate" but apparently without success.
The boy hid it from his family.
He decided to take his illness on his own shoulders and began to inform himself about it, with such dedication that he had already celebrated his 43rd birthday.
He is undoubtedly one of the most recent patients of the HIV Unit at the Civil Hospital of Guadalajara (HCG), which he came to in 1994 after several battles with the disease.
Fabrizio has been living with human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) for 22 years, something unimaginable in the early 1990s, when there was a lot of doubt, little treatment options and more stigma.
At the time, even the director of the Mexican Institute of Social Security (IMSS) clinic did not say goodbye to him, “because he had a cutting wound.”
At that time, having AIDS was synonymous with death.
Now it is possible to survive with this syndrome and live fully.
However, there are many people who do not know about their disease and come only when the virus has caused destruction of the body and strengthened the immune system, and then become victims of accidental infections.
31 years since the appearance of AIDS in the world, or at least since the first documented cases, "the success of the disease means that the length of life of the patient, who begins treatment in a timely and appropriate manner, is exactly the same as in healthy people," said Jaime Andrade Villanueva, head of the Department of Health, in a press release.
