Simply put, this means that someone diagnosed with HIV at the age of 25 can “live without problems for up to 75 years if treatment is followed,” the doctor explained in an interview.
To emphasize this progress, it is worth recalling that the average life expectancy of Mexicans today is 76 years.
Although mortality has declined significantly in recent years, and in the case of Mexico, the number of people who died of AIDS has fallen from 6,678 in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (anniversary of the Joint United Nations Programme on HIV/AIDS - UNAIDS), it is also true that 60 percent of patients have died since the discovery of AIDS, according to national statistics.
In Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011 and 187 so far in May, but universal access to antiretrovirals has been ensured since 2005.
