The judgment passed by the United States Court of Appeals, which does not recognise the restructuring of Grupo Vitro’s debt as set out in the Mexican tender, sets a bad precedent for any national firm with branches in a neighbouring country and a solvency problem.
Thus, the procedures for restructuring companies that allow Mexican laws do not seem to apply in the country of the stripes and stars, despite international agreements.
The approval of the judgment issued on June 15 last year by Judge Harlin Hale at the bankruptcy court for North Texas leaves the Mexican company defenseless against the possibility of confiscation of their property on the other bank of the El Bravo River.
However, the ruling opens the door for the main Mexican glass manufacturer to the Supreme Court of the United States with an appeal against three irregularities.
The opening is to say that while the judge of this case claims that creditors are to be governed by the United States Insolvency Act, the New Orleans-based Fifth District Court of Appeals says that the main procedure sets out the bankruptcy proceedings in Mexico.
Firstly, this would indicate a lack of knowledge of international procedural cooperation in cases of insolvency of multinational enterprises.
In essence, the United Nations Model Law for the Unification of International Commercial Law was created for this purpose, which is determined by the arbitrator of the American Law Institute.
Secondly, the judgment provides that, without the votes of the branches of the internal company structure, when the debts of the parent company Vitro to the branches are recognised, the required majority for the approval of the restructuring would not have been reached.
However, this option is allowed by Mexican law.
The fact is that the Vitro case was not the first in which this scheme was adopted.
There are half a dozen examples, such as Agrimex and Comercial Mexicana, for which the Federal Institute of Compulsory Liabilities was responsible.
In addition, it is true that even after deduction of the votes of the branches, creditors - who stood against Vitro in court in the United States, i.e. funds of "supposeds", such as Aurelios Capital, Aurelios Convergencia, Elliot Internacional and Liverpool Limited - would not reach a majority.
In the vote, they would reach about 45 percent to 37.
This information shall not be taken into account by the Court of Appeal.
From another point of view, the court blames Vitro for the difficult situation it has faced since 2008 – against the backdrop of a serious economic crisis that has hit the United States.
In the meantime, the family firm Gonz<0xC3><0xA1>lez Sady will appeal to the Court of Appeal for a new assessment, so that the assessment can be carried out with the full participation, i.e. with the participation of five judges, because initially only three of them voted.
If it does not succeed here, it will require, as an appeal, a review of the process by the higher courts, in this case the Supreme Court of the United States.
In the case, it is significant that the court omitted a document sent by the Mexican government as an amicus curiae service, detailing Vitro’s procedure under the Competition Act and pointing out that the company had made it easier to comply with the agreements signed by the two countries in order to comply with the law.
Furthermore, it points out that the country has complied with the principles of the United Nations Commission on International Trade, i.e. the rules laid down for international insolvency cases, which guarantee equality for debtors and creditors.
