Héctor "Hetin" Reyes: "Basketball was my life"
Basketball world champion Héctor "Hetin" Reyes has been associated with this hall sport for more than 60 years and thanks to him has traveled the world.
Few people in Puerto Rico have as many memories of the history of local basketball as Héctor "Hetin" Reyes has.
Reyes was before he was hit by a brain stroke on a wheelchair in 2008, having been involved in the sport for more than 60 years, whether as a junior category player, player of the BSN National Basketball League, owner and coach of the Vaqueros de Bayam<0xC3><0xB3>n team in the National Basketball League, or as a president.
“I’ve held many roles in basketball throughout my life, including several at the same time, such as being president of the BSN National League in the 1990s, managing director of the national team and chairman of the federation,” Reyes recalled while visiting reporters of Primera Hora’s newspaper at his home in Bayam<0xC3><0xB3>n.
"Basketball was my life."
Reyes does not go overboard in his claim.
The walls of his house, which are almost all decorated with photos and commemorative items from his long career, testify to this.
Bayam<0xC3><0xB3>n in the heart
With the greatest momentum of all the guards, those who recall his performance in Los Vaqueros from the mid-1950s, where he was a player until 1982, when at the same time he celebrated 15 years as a co-owner or owner of the team.
“It has been my best years, the one I have enjoyed the most, because I have had the opportunity to participate in eight championships with the Los Vaqueros team since 1967, whether as an owner, co-owner, or coach.
It was a series of successful years, including five championships held from 1971 to 1975.
And then I said goodbye to one championship - in 1981, when Jerome Mincy made his BSN debut.
At that time, the team took over "Cuco" Ortiz, who was an excellent leader," Reyes said.
“I remember Gene Bartow, who was here as a coach at the time at the University of Alabama in Birmingham, telling me, ‘I have a mature two-meter player for you.
Do you want him?"
And that was the beginning of Mincy, one of the best players Puerto Rico has ever had.
Bartow then recommended to me the player Raymond Gausse, who became a member of the team and one of our best shooters.
I remember he said that if Mincy brought Bayamon a championship win, then Gauss would contribute to the next one.”
He enjoyed the championship, when he played for the team of los Vaqueros, Gausse, but only remotely, because in 1988 he already served as president of the basketball federation.
At the time, he wanted to devote himself fully to his duties and enjoy Mincy’s place in the national team.
“I remember the first time we beat the United States in the 1989 Olympic qualifier in Mexico.
Then came the 1990 World Cup, where we finished fourth, but we should have had the bronze if it wasn't for the Canadian referee who let us repeat the final pitch," Reyes said.
Is the 1990 World Cup team the best national team you've ever seen?
He is among the best, as well as the one who defeated the Dream Team at the 2004 Olympics.
But my favorite was the national team at the 1991 Pan American Games in Cuba, when we won the gold and scratched out a United States team that was quite similar to the one that blew up our bronze for the World Cup.
The team had not only Mincy, Gausse, Ramon Rivase, Fica L<0xC3><0xB3>pez and "Picul<0xC3><0xAD>na" (Ortiz), but also young men (Javier) "To<0xC3><0xB1>ito" Col<0xC3><0xB3>n and James Carter, brothers Leon (Francisco and Edgar) and Mario "Quijote" Morales, who could not be in the team at will in 1990.
The team, which may not have had a perfect composition, but managed to win a gold medal and bring great joy, was the team from the Olympic qualifiers in 1995 in Neuquén, Argentina.
With players on the roster such as "Canito" Nieves, Pablo Alicea and junior player Rolando Hourruitiner replacing players excluded due to a fight in the Pan American Games in Mar de Plata, we have won the gold despite all the predictions.
What was the best player in Puerto Rico?
It was without a doubt Picul<0xC3><0xAD>n Ortiz.
His numbers from international tournaments are impressive.
No one in Puerto Rico has achieved at this level such results as Picul<0xC3><0xAD>n.
Not to mention his performance in various leagues where he played.
Who was the best Puerto Rican coach?
That's very hard.
We had a very good generation, which includes Julio Toro, Flor Meléndez, Carlos Morales, Raymond Dalmau and Armandito Torres.
I like the work of Leo Arilla.
What do you consider to be your greatest achievement in the world?
That I was part of the most famous era of the national team from 1988 to 1995 and that at the beginning of the 90s the national league BSN had up to 17 teams in one season.
What have you failed to prove?
There were things that I wanted to introduce, like the division of youth categories by region.
For example, the boys from Ponce would play only in their area and compete with teams from other corners of the island only in the national play-offs.
Now the kids travel a lot and play a lot of games, which is not necessary.
I also see the benefit in mandatory certificates and courses for coaches, assistant referees and referees.
I'm glad to hear that.
What are you doing now?
I listen to music the most, watch YouTube videos with music from my time, enjoy my grandchildren and sometimes go to basketball games.
And of course I enjoy the company of my wife Isabel, who has always been by my side.
Actor Larry Hagman has died.
Larry Hagman, who was born on September 21, 1931 in Forth Worth, Texas, world-renowned for starring John Ross Ewing, better known as "J.R." in the television series Dallas, in which he portrayed a man who acted ruthlessly and was insidious and manipulative.
Larry Hagman, whose role as oil tycoon J.R. Ewing on the television series Dallas became a symbol of hunger in the 1980s, died.
He was 81 years old.
Hagman, who returned this year as J.R. in the new Dallas series, died on Friday afternoon of complications associated with cancer, according to an official family announcement given to the Associated Press by the Dallas-based production company Warner Bros..
“Larry returned to his beloved hometown of Dallas, where he again played the iconic role he loved best,” his family said in a statement.
Larry's family and his closest friends were in Dallas on Thanksgiving.
"Linda Gray, who was his wife's representative in both the original and the new series, was with Hagman at the time of his death at a hospital in Dallas," her agent Jeffrey Lane said in a statement.
He brought joy to everyone he knew.
"He was creative, generous, funny, kind, kind and talented and I will miss him very much.
He was unique and lived his life to the fullest," Linda Gray said in a statement.
Hagman was diagnosed with liver cirrhosis in 1992, and he admitted to drinking heavily for years.
In 1995, a malignant tumor was found on his liver and Hagman underwent a transplant.
Years before the series aired in Dallas, Hagman became famous on television as a decent guy in the light comedy I Dream of Jeannie aired on NBC from 1965 to 1970.
Here he played the character of Captain Tony Nelson, an astronaut whose life changes when he meets an attractive girl (genius) played by Barbara Eden, and takes her home to live together.
He also starred in two short-lived comedies, The Good Life (NBC, 1971–72) and Here We Go Again (ABC, 1973).
His performance in films included roles that were well received by critics: The Group, Harry and Tonto and Primary Colors.
But it wasn’t until Hangman’s masterful performance in the form of an incredibly repulsive J.R. that he was taken to the starry top.
The CBS drama series about the Ewing clan and other personalities around them was broadcast from April 1978 to May 1991.
The propaganda slogan "Who shot Jayar?", which was supposed to raise expectations about the work of full emotion, when Hangman's character is almost murdered, caused not only a huge number of speculation by viewers around the world, but also risking millions of dollars in the betting offices.
This also helped this work to achieve a record in tracking.
The November 1980 episode, in which the answer was revealed, was watched by an average of 41 million television viewers, making Dallas the second most watched entertainment show in history after the conclusion of the 1983 MASH series, which watched 50 million viewers.
J.R. was shot by his brother-in-law Kristin (played by Mary Crosby).
Kristin and J.R. got pregnant, and he threatened to call her a prostitute if she didn't leave town, but there were others who had reason to attack him.
Hagman played Ewing, an insatiable greedy man with a charismatic smile: a greedy businessman and an unfaithful husband who tried to get his wife Sue Ellen (Linda Gray), an alcoholic, to be locked up in a medical facility.
"I know what I want J.R. to have on the tombstone," Hagman said in 1988.
It should be, "Here lies the honorable citizen J.R. Ewing."
This is the only thing that didn't work out.
Victoria Principal, who played in the original series, recalled Hagman as someone who was "excellent on and off the screen" on Friday.
It is unforgettable and irreplaceable for millions of fans around the world and in the hearts of all of us who have been fortunate enough to know and love it.
Ten episodes of the new Dallas series aired on TNT a few months ago with great success.
"Five parts of the second series have already been filmed and the sixth has just been filmed," the television station said.
Immediately after Hangman's death, there were no statements from Warner or TNT about how the series would continue.
A native of Fort Worth, Texas, he was the son of actress and singer Mary Martin, who starred in classics such as South Pacific and Peter Pan.
Mary Martin was a very young girl when in 1931 she gave birth to Larry, whose father was her husband, lawyer Ben Hagman.
In the early 1950s, Larry tried his luck on stage in New York, and then served in the Air Force in England from 1952 to 1956.
There he met young Swedish designer Maj Axelsson, whom he married.
The couple had two children, Preston and Heidi, and lived for a long time in the California town of Malibu, where many celebrities reside.
In 2001, he published the autobiographical book Hello Darlin': Tall (and Absolutely True) Tales about My Life.
"I didn't put anything there that I knew could hurt someone or hurt them in any way," he told Prensa Asociada.
After the liver transplant, he began to promote organ donation and worked as a volunteer in a hospital where he helped patients who were afraid.
