Begins a course that explores the "end of the world"
Every week, students explore apocalyptic topics such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and bacteria, and global warming.
When religion professor Stuart Charmé decided to take this semester’s course on the end of the world, he knew it was an irresistible allure: the end of the Mayan calendar’s “long count” due to come on December 21st was caught by many people as proof that the end of the world was coming.
However, Charmé had no idea what would happen to him in the next few months: the catastrophic Hurricane Sandy, a budget rift that some call the "debt of Armageddon," and the growing conflict in which Israel is drawn, a place where Christians theorize the end of the world.
"I didn't realize this was going to be the most apocalyptic semester it's ever been," Charmé told students this week at Rutgers University in Camden, New Jersey.
“When you look at what’s happening in the world today as if we have 30 days left, it’s a really good time.
And remember, bad means good for the apocalyptically minded.
And that’s not the only professor to offer courses on the “end of the world” in this semester, which is theoretically the last in history.
Barry Vacker, an assistant professor at Temple University, teaches a course on “Environment, Culture, and the End of the World.”
Every week, students explore apocalyptic topics such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and bacteria, and global warming.
"We understand why these ideas expand over time," he says, and how they offer hypothetical scenarios that govern certain human behavior.
For example, if nuclear material gets into the hands of terrorists, a war can break out.
This month, students analyze films with apocalyptic themes and explore how they differ from real-life examples.
“I’ve tried to inform students about what’s possible, probable, believable, and impossible,” says Vacker.
On the main campus of the State University of Pennsylvania, Latin American History Professor Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, an assistant professor of art history and anthropology, joined forces to organize a course with the simple name End of the World.
“We don’t join 2012 because we always expect to be able to set the course again if the world doesn’t end,” Restall said.
Despite the “threat of destruction,” students must study, create projects, and take final exams.
At Penn State, the final exam will take place on the eve of the Apocalypse, giving students no choice but to work “until the very evening of the predicted end of the world,” Restall said.
The courses have become quite popular.
"It's spread out in two hours," Restall said of his course for high-medium students who turned 35.
Weeks and weeks before the start of the semester, we received an email asking if there was still room.
The students themselves assure that the course is one of the most interesting.
“I find it fascinating to see what people are doing to comfort themselves,” said Bridgid Robinson, a 23-year-old student in the field of religion and sociology from Haddonfield, New Jersey, at Rutgers University in Camden.
Thus, apocalyptic, secular or religious thinking is only a matter of comfort or its absence.
Will Wekes, a 25-year-old psychology and nursing student, said he had seen all the apocalyptic movies.
"I've never heard of an hour in which it could be taught," he said.
"I'm enjoying it."
But no confidant student, let alone a professor, has said that he believes in the date of the end of December 21.
“Our first project was about the Mayan prediction, and in a way, we’re rejecting it,” said Julie Zeglen, a 21-year-old senior student at Temple University in West Chester.
"The Mayans never predicted the end of the world; it's just a key point in the calendar," Restall said.
But he added that in Western culture there is an apocalyptic anxiety that goes back several centuries, which people react to changes in their surroundings with predictions about the end of the world.
The rise of these speculations has caused the Internet.
"People don't think about it," he said.
This is the case in the vast majority of the English-speaking world.
Joseph Dougherty, a professor of religion at La Salle University, who is giving a lecture in the Philippines this year, asked if he knew of a course there on the “end of the world.”
"The Philippines is not taking part in the end of the world," he wrote, suggesting an exception at the highest office.
We have the grace of the Pope.
Restall noted that over the years there has been talk of many days of last judgment, and said that if nothing happens on December 21, "people will start thinking immediately about the next date" or philosophizing that December 21 is the beginning of a seven-year period at the end of which the world will disappear.
Students and professors take the date lightly.
Several of them have said that they intend to go to the celebration of the "end of the world".
"I think I'll call a few friends to laugh together," said 20-year-old communications student Samira Ford.
